Recently fledged young bird.  Family reported earlier in the day, did not see adults.  I got down to the Presidio around 5pm this evening.  With David Tomb, we were able to pretty quickly get on what appears to be a recently fledged Lawrence’s Goldfinch.  (Someone please correct me if I’m wrong!). Note the white in the tail, the yellow already coming in on the wing, the pale head and large bill - all of which I think safely separate this from the other finches.  We stayed with this bird for about ten minutes and then it flew off with another (possibly juvenile, possibly adult female.). This was at the coordinates that Lee Hong-Chang gave in the first post.  Over the next hour I was unable to get on any other LAGOs - though I heard the tinkle call a few times.  It was difficult with the high winds and the literally hundred plus House Finch, Lesser Goldfinch, juncos, song and WC sparrows, and Hooded Orioles flying around.  This area seems to be a breeding frenzy.   You should also check the trees in a little gully about 100 yards north of the spot (not accessible by any main trail) where I last heard the LAGO call.  Are there any other breeding records of this bird in San Francisco in modern times?

Better views desired.  Refound the bird with Pat Kenny, Roland, and one other birder whose name I didn't get.  Was very active around the east end of the green lawn.   First saw in flight with pipits, smaller, more distinctive face pattern and very wide white outer rectices, quite noticable in flight.  Flew up to small hill, where we found it on 3 different occasions near the top of the ridge.  Also seen briefly on the lawn and in the large grassy "overflow parking" area.  My impression is that the bird is mellower  when foraging than the pipits, but tends to take off with the flock when the pipits get edgy.  I think it would be approachable, though I only had 4 distant and brief views.  I stuck around for an hour afterward hoping to get a better photo, but was unable to refind, even though the pipits continued to come and go.

First SF record found by Hugh Cotter 10/9/17.  Small Sparrow sized-bird appeared very tame -  observed feeding for about 15 minutes on berm on the northern side of the great field.  Appears to be a young (first fall?) female.  Numerous field marks to separate from similar Chestnut-collared.  Note large pink bill with black tip.  Pale face with plain auriculars around unremarkable ear covert.  Wide pale supercilium - overall head color somewhat reminiscent of a female House Sparrow.  Bird had a buffy collar similar to head and not "chestnut.  Notable buffy breast-plate with barely any streaking coming to a crisp transition.  Breast patch remarkably similar in shape to that of the black breast patch of an adult male McCowns.  Median coverts were darker than other feathers - good field mark, though not as dark as an immature male, led me to think this is female.  Bird in flight had wide white patches on outer rectices.  Flew short-distances (20-50 meters) at low height - unlike a LALO.  Only called in flight.  This was my #600 ABA-Continental bird!

(from EBB) We couldn't re-find the Clay-colored this morning.  But this LARK BUNTING was a nice prize.   Here is a photo:  I saw the Bunting three times each time near the gravel path. The spot was extremely birdy this morning - much more than previous days - with maybe 500 sparrows actively feeding, including Song, Fox, W-C, G-C, Lincoln's, and Towhees in big numbers - along with a higher count of Goldfinches.    As I was leaving, a much smaller White-crowned Sparrow was harassing the Lark Bunting, very close to the car park area.

photos.Observation Details: One flew from W side of harbor mouth to Jetty on E. Initially spotted by Peter Metropulos. Pished in for better views, and photos were taken. Overall a Savannah Sparrow with greyish tone to back, and very indistinct back streaking. No white "suspenders" on upperparts. Similarly underpart streaking dull and not as distinct as on typical Savannah. Overall a long-billed Savannah, but this was less noticeable than the lack of contrast in markings. Extremely rare in Northern California, but Pillar Point Harbor has become a place where sightings have occurred in the last few years. A first, a lifer, for Alvaro! Very exciting to see this from the boat!

photos.Observation Details: Found by Mark Rauzon 10/6/15.  SF City first.  Very flightly, mostly on low branches from 1-10' off ground, not on the ground much.  Bird has the narrow broken eye ring and yellowish throat that eliminate MacGillivrays, (not shown well in these photos) and a yellowish supra-loral.  Bright yellow body.  First winter bird.

Noah Arthur and I were chatting on facebook this morning about searching for rarities along the Eastshore after the first rain of the fall. Then he goes out and quickly finds a first county record Mourning Warbler. I arrived at about 12:40pm and searched with him and Judi Sierra for about 40 minutes until we refound it. The bird is very secretive (like all MOWA as far as I know) and tended to stay in about a 100 ft radius of heavy riparian willow, thick clumps of grass and low branches.  Was feeding on the ground or lowest branches, never seen more than about 24" off the ground.  Did not allow particularly close approach. Juvenal plumage - presumed first year - sex indeterminate. Gray head, narrow white broken eye-ring "eye arcs" - fully broken by dark horizontal line.   The throat is off-white directly at the base of the lower mandible, but otherwise yellow.  Gray broken breast-band does not form a complete hood as MGWA (MacGillivray's) would.  Breast and underparts a convincing bright yellow that gave it an overall feel of n OCWA/. Tail seemed notably short.   Although 1st winter MOWA and MGWA are similar, I feel that the presence of yellow superloral, yellow throat, and thin eye arcs cinch the ID.  Bird behavior was also MOWA like, skulking and staying low to the ground or on dirt at all times. The creek makes up the county line.  When I arrived Noah had seen it on both sides of the creek (he initially found it bathing).  We refound it on the Contra Costa side where it stayed for about an hour - only allowing a few open views.  As I was leaving, Derek Heins refound the bird on the Alameda side, where it stayed at the water's edge for some time.

Found by Logan Kahle this morning.   Adult male, in the thick willow riparian near the junction of Steam Trail x Eucalyptus Trail.   For the first half hour I heard the 'basic' song exactly three times from the far side of the stream perhaps 100 yards through dense thicket from the trail - I also repeatedly heard a short four-note call that I was not familiar with that sounded like the last four notes of the basic song.  Pretty sure that is the same bird.   Finally he decided to check out my pishing (no play-back) and flew over to me - for the next 15 minutes or so he sang repeatedly from perches around the trail.  Hooded Warblers are strong confident flyers in the understory with a clear loud song.

I found this Blackburnian on the island at 2:33pm, in tall trees on the shore across from the Boat House - almost directly across the lake from where Nancy Palmer reported one this morning.  It was in a small flock of about 10 Yellow & Townsend's Warblers + 1 BTYW.   I was not able to get a good photo of it, and gave up as it worked its way higher into the cypresses.  But I did get good looks at it initially and also in flight, and was confident in my ID. Small warbler - similar to Townsend's but with a more compact elongated shape and a more direct flight style.  Head not as rounded as Townsend's.  Bird appears to be 1st winter.   Wide unbroken white wing bars and a black back that matched the wings, not gray (TOWA) or Green (CERW).  I did not get a good look at any detail "braces" on the back and the poor photos don't show anything, but the color was definitive.   Yellow wash extends unbroken acros the throat and breast almost to the legs.  Streaked on flanks, not excessively.   Head has the typical gray triangular auriculars of a Blackburnian, but not very well defined in the back, which was smudgy yellow and gray.   Defining feature is the lengthy yellow supercilium extending all the way to the nape, and the lower eye crescent that appears white in the photos.   Combination of all of these traits ufficient to eliminate TOWA.  A couple things bother me about this bird however.  The photos seem to show a long tail with extendsive black on the sides, which is somewhat forked, kind of like a Parula.   None of this looks typical for either BLWA nor TOWA.  Also the bird has a somewhat well defined eye arcs in one of the photos though that may be a trick of the angle.  Considered other species. Face pattern, black back and sharp white wing bar are all a good match for BLWA however.
